### Set Basics

A Set is an unordered collection of unique items. Duplicates are automatically removed.

```dart
void main() {
  // Creating sets
  Set<int> numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
  var fruits = {'apple', 'banana', 'orange'};
  var empty = <String>{};

  // Accessing elements
  print(fruits.length); // 3
  print(fruits.contains('apple')); // true

  // Adding and removing
  fruits.add('grape');
  fruits.add('apple'); // Duplicate - ignored
  fruits.remove('banana');

  print(fruits); // {apple, orange, grape}
}
```

### Set Operations

```dart
void main() {
  var setA = {1, 2, 3, 4};
  var setB = {3, 4, 5, 6};

  // Union
  var union = setA.union(setB);
  print(union); // {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}

  // Intersection
  var intersection = setA.intersection(setB);
  print(intersection); // {3, 4}

  // Difference
  var difference = setA.difference(setB);
  print(difference); // {1, 2}
}
```

### Set Methods

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `add(element)` | Adds element | `set.add(5)` |
| `addAll(iterable)` | Adds multiple | `set.addAll([5,6])` |
| `remove(element)` | Removes element | `set.remove(3)` |
| `contains(element)` | Checks membership | `set.contains(3)` |
| `clear()` | Removes all | `set.clear()` |
| `union(other)` | Elements in either | `a.union(b)` |
| `intersection(other)` | Common elements | `a.intersection(b)` |
| `difference(other)` | In a but not b | `a.difference(b)` |
| `lookup(element)` | Finds element or null | `set.lookup(3)` |

### Set Properties

```dart
void main() {
  var set = {1, 2, 3};

  print(set.length);    // 3
  print(set.isEmpty);   // false
  print(set.isNotEmpty); // true
  print(set.first);     // 1 (order not guaranteed)
  print(set.last);      // 3
}
```

### Converting Between Sets and Lists

```dart
void main() {
  var list = [1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4];

  // Remove duplicates by converting to set
  var unique = list.toSet();
  print(unique); // {1, 2, 3, 4}

  // Convert back to list
  var uniqueList = unique.toList();
  print(uniqueList); // [1, 2, 3, 4]
}
```

> **Key Point:** Sets are ideal for storing unique values. Use `toSet()` to remove duplicates from a list. Set operations like `union()`, `intersection()`, and `difference()` are very efficient.

